Introducing WAT.ai's latest project: Mechanistic Interpretability!The project focuses on training a simple transformer to understand basic arithmetic operations and analyze its learning mechanisms, including the identification of polysemantic or superposition neurons.By examining the transformer's behavior and employing a sparse autoencoder, we aim to transform complex activations into interpretable formats. This research will provide insights into how neural networks generalize learning and enhance AI interpretability.Ultimately, this work seeks to bridge the gap between complex AI operations and human-understandable interpretations.Applications are open! If you have any questions feel free to reach out!Application link: https://forms.gle/aspSiAfgu2yYMwyh7(also in bio)Deadline: February 25, 2024

Warming temperatures mean shorter ice seasons in Sanikiluaq, Nunavut. As a result, the stretches of landfast ice formed from frozen seawater that Inuit use to travel and hunt on are increasingly unpredictable and unsafe. Neil Brubacher, a recent MASc graduate from the Faculty of Engineering, led a community sea ice safety project as part of his thesis that leveraged artificial intelligence (AI) to make on-ice travel safer with accurate and timely data easily available, with a partnership between the University of Waterloo‚Äôs Vision and Imaging Processing (VIP) and the Sanikiluaq-based Arctic Eider Society (AES). From developing aerogels that absorb oil spills to critical research on the future of drinking water, Waterloo Engineering is leading the development of sustainable solutions. Milad Kamkar, a professor in chemical engineering, has designed novel types of ultralightweight aerogels that fight all kinds of pollutants. Did you know that over 70% of the world‚Äôs drinking water originates in forests? Happy World Engineering Day!

üì£ Big news - the Global Engagement Seminar: Me and My Robot is opening its special lecture series to everyone for the first time!Join the 2024 Jarislowsky Fellows, leading experts & practitioners in the field, as we explore the social, physical, and practical interfaces between humans and robots and what their presence in our everyday environments will mean for ourselves and society.All lectures are happening in Engineering 5, Room 3102 and include a talk and Q&A.ü§ñ Unfamiliar Intelligence: Art, Exoticism, Robots, and AI (Feb 7, 8:00-9:30PM)Ken Goldberg is an artist, inventor, and professor at the University of California, Berkeley. UW's first in person GIS day since 2019 will be taking place on November 15th between 1:00 and 4:00 PM in the Geospatial Centre (Dana Porter Library). There is a packed agenda of lightning talks and workshops this year (be sure to sign up using the link if you want to do a workshop), Google Earth VR will be on offer, and there will be free cake and coffee at the event. If you want to learn more about the exciting GIS projects that are happening all across campus or pick up some new GIS skills (e.g. Python in GIS and Web Mapping with JavaScript), this is the event for you!

üåü Honouring a Rich Legacy: Why February for Black History Month? üåç‚úä‚Ä®February is more than just a month on the calendar; it‚Äôs a profound tribute to the incredible journey and contributions of the Black community.‚Ä®üìÜ Historical Significance: Did you know that February was chosen for Black History Month because it aligns with the birthdays of two monumental figures? Abraham Lincoln, the 16th President of the United States, who issued the Emancipation Proclamation, and Frederick Douglass, an eminent abolitionist and social reformer, both share this month. ‚Ä®üåà Celebrating Diversity: Black History Month provides a dedicated space to celebrate the diverse narratives, achievements, and resilience of the Black community. üåê‚Ä®üîç Education and Empowerment: By designating February for this celebration, the aim is to raise awareness, educate, and empower individuals to appreciate the profound impact Black history has had on society. It‚Äôs a collective effort to foster understanding, break down stereotypes, and pave the way for a more inclusive future. üìöüëè‚Ä®Let‚Äôs embrace this month as an opportunity to learn, grow, and stand in solidarity with the Black community. Together, we build a world where every story is heard, valued, and celebrated. üåé‚Ä®Ô∏è #BlackHistoryMonth
